  "prompt": "Why don't Google merged Allo and Duo to make one single app?",
  "response": "Google's decision not to merge Allo and Duo into a single app likely stemmed from its strategy to address different communication needs with distinct solutions. Allo was designed as a smart messaging app with a focus on rich text communication and smart replies, incorporating Google Assistant features. Duo, on the other hand, was specifically focused on video calling with an emphasis on simplicity and reliability.\n\nSome possible reasons for keeping them separate may include:\n\n1. **Different Use Cases**: Allo and Duo catered to different types of communication\u2014text-based versus video-based. Users who preferred texting may not necessarily use video calling, and vice versa.\n\n2. **Technical Specialization**: Merging two apps with different technical infrastructures could be complex and may not deliver the best user experience. By keeping them separate, each app could be optimized independently for its specific function.\n\n3. **Market Segmentation**: Having separate apps allowed Google to target different market segments. Video calling apps like Duo can compete directly with services like FaceTime and Skype, while messaging apps like Allo can focus on competing with WhatsApp and Messenger.\n\nHowever, despite the differentiation, Google eventually phased out Allo and focused its efforts on Messages, a more versatile messaging app with RCS features. Duo has now been integrated with Google Meet, which has evolved to be a more comprehensive communication tool. This consolidation aligns with Google's broader strategy to streamline its communication tools and reduce fragmentation.",
